8 Sec. 3. NRS 289.605 is hereby amended to read as follows:
9 289.605 1. The Commission shall require, as a condition of the certification
10 of each peace officer, the completion of training concerning identifying and
11 interacting with persons with developmental disabilities. Such training must
12 include, without limitation, at least 4 hours of in-person training concerning:
13 (a) The nature and manifestation of autism spectrum disorders;
14 (b) Appropriate techniques for interviewing or interrogating a person with
15 an autism spectrum disorder;
16 (c) Techniques for locating a person with an autism spectrum disorder who
17 is missing and in danger, with as little stress as possible for the person with an
18 autism spectrum disorder;
19 (d) Techniques for recognizing the agency of a person with an autism
20 spectrum disorder while identifying potentially abusive or coercive situations;
21 (e) Techniques for deescalating a potentially dangerous situation involving a
22 person with an autism spectrum disorder to protect the safety of the peace officer
23 and the person with an autism spectrum disorder;
24 (f) Techniques for differentiating between a person with an autism spectrum
25 disorder and a person who does not have an autism spectrum disorder but is
26 acting belligerently, uncooperatively or otherwise similarly to a person with an
27 autism spectrum disorder;
28 (g) Procedures to identify and address challenges related to the safety of
29 persons with an autism spectrum disorder in correctional facilities; and
30 (h) The impact of interacting with peace officers on persons with autism
31 spectrum disorders.
32 2. Training completed pursuant to this section also satisfies the requirement
33 for such training prescribed by NRS 450B.160 or 450B.180, if applicable.
34 3. As used in this section, “developmental disability” has the meaning
35 ascribed to it in NRS 435.007.
